an attempt to abandon the notion that journalists and their audiences are spectators in political and social processes. In its place, the ___ journalism movement seeks to treat readers and community members as participants.","wiki"),("gonzo","5","___ journalism is a style of journalism that is written without claims of objectivity, often including the reporter as part of the story via a first-person narrative. The word '___' is believed to have been first used in 1970 to describe an article by Hunter S. Thompson, who later popularized the style. It is an energetic first-person participatory writing style in which the author is a protagonist, and it draws its power from a combination of social critique and self-satire. It has since been applied to other subjective artistic endeavors.","wiki"),("peace","5","This concept was proposed by Johan Galtung","wiki"),("genre","5","___  with socially-agreed-upon conventions developed over time. ___ is most popularly known as a category of literature, music, or other forms of art or entertainment, whether written or spoken, audio or visual, based on some set of stylistic criteria, yet ___s can be aesthetic, rhetorical, communicative, or functional. ___s form by conventions that change over time as cultures invent new ___s and discontinue the use of old ones. Often, works fit into multiple ___s by way of borrowing and recombining these conventions. Stand-alone texts, works, or pieces of communication may have individual styles, but ___s are amalgams of these texts based on agreed-upon or socially inferred conventions. Some ___s may have rigid, strictly adhered-to guidelines, while others may show great flexibility.","wiki"),("divus","5","Deus, 'god'; dea, 'goddess', plural deae; di or dii, 'gods', plural, or 'deities', of mixed gender. The Greek equivalent is theos, which the Romans translated with deus. Servius says  Compare ___. For etymological discussion, see Deus and Dyeus. See also List of Roman deities.","wiki"),("juche","